  "bib_entries": {
    "35753274": {
      "title": "Two refinements of the bound of Sauer, Perles and Shelah, and of Vapnik and Chervonenkis",
      "abstract": "We say that a matrix is simple if it is a (0, 1)-matrix with no repeated columns. Given m and a kxl (0, 1)-matrix F, we seek the bound forb(m,F) on the maximum number of columns that a simple m-rowed matrix A can have if the simple matrix A has the property that it has no kxl submatrix which is a row and column permutation of F. Let K\"k denote the kx2^k (0, 1)-matrix of all columns in k rows. Sauer, Perles and Shelah, and Vapnik and Chervonenkis established that forb(m,K\"k) is @Q(m^k^-^1). (An alternative description for the absence of a configuration K\"k is to say that the matrix has no shattered k-set.) We identify an easy but exact condition on a k-rowed simple matrix F for which forb(m,F) is O(m^k^-^2). A consequence is a classification of the asymptotics of forb(m,F) for simple four-rowed matrices F. In addition we identify an easy but exact description for all k-rowed non-simple matrices F which contain K\"k and for which forb(m,F) is still O(m^k^-^1). The results are further evidence for the conjecture of Anstee and Sali on the asymptotics of forb(m,F) for fixed F."
    }
  },
